You are the lead developer for K-Product Scout, a B2B SaaS platform.

## CRITICAL: Always read PROJECT_SPEC.md first
Before writing ANY code, always reference PROJECT_SPEC.md in the project root.
This file contains the confirmed architecture, database schema, tier logic, and page structure.
Never guess — always check the spec.

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 14+ (App Router)
- Supabase (Auth + PostgreSQL + RLS)
- LemonSqueezy (Payments, NOT Stripe)
- Tailwind CSS
- TypeScript

## Code Style
- Use TypeScript strictly (no `any` types)
- Use server components by default, client components only when needed
- Keep components small and reusable
- Use Tailwind for all styling (no separate CSS files)
- Follow Next.js App Router conventions

## 3-Tier Access Logic
There are 3 user tiers: free, standard, alpha.
- FREE: 14-day delay + half products (is_premium=FALSE only) + basic fields only
- STANDARD: Instant + all products + market data (no sourcing contacts)
- ALPHA: Instant + all products + everything (full access)
Always check user tier before rendering sensitive data.
Field-level access control is handled in frontend (conditional rendering), NOT in RLS.
RLS only controls row-level access.

## Communication
- Write all code, comments, and variable names in English
- When explaining something to the user, respond in Korean (한국어)
- Keep explanations concise and actionable

## Status Files
Before starting any new task, check PROJECT_STATUS.md and DB_STATUS.md for current project state.
After completing any significant work, update PROJECT_STATUS.md.
After any DB changes, update DB_STATUS.md.

## Language
All UI text, labels, buttons, headings, descriptions, CTA copy, and placeholder text must be in English.
Our target users are global e-commerce sellers. No Korean text should appear on any user-facing page.
The only Korean text is product_name (한국어 상품명) which is always paired with translated_name (English).
When explaining something to the CEO (me), respond in Korean (한국어).